\section{URL enumeration}{

EA-Hub is a Vue SPA sitting on a public REST API at
\verb{https://eahub.miljoeportal.dk/api/} (Swagger lives at
\verb{/api/swagger/v1/swagger.json}). One \code{POST /assessments/search} call
returns the entire register (~2700 records at the time of writing); each
row already carries title, year range, status, authorities, EIA-Directive
Annex I/II categories, plan types/categories, and a \code{hasGeometry} flag.
No detail call is needed during the scan phase — every field a downstream
classifier needs is present in the search response.
}

\section{Geometry}{

Records with \code{hasGeometry == TRUE} carry a polygon (typically a
MULTIPOLYGON in EPSG:25832 / ETRS89-UTM32N — the standard Danish
projection). When \code{write_sidecar = TRUE}, the geometry is fetched from
\code{GET /assessments/{id}/geometry} and saved next to the sidecar as
\verb{<document_id>.geometry.geojson}. The sidecar carries \code{geometry_path}
(absolute path to the .geojson) and \code{geometry_crs} (\code{"EPSG:25832"}).

The GeoJSON is written with the GeoJSON-2008 \code{crs} member naming
\verb{urn:ogc:def:crs:EPSG::25832}; tools like QGIS / \code{sf::read_sf()} read
this fine, even though RFC 7946 deprecated the field. Coordinates are
kept in the source CRS — reproject downstream with \code{sf} if you need
WGS84.
}

\section{Attachments}{

EA-Hub exposes PDFs at public Azure blob URLs reachable via
\code{GET /assessments/{id}/documents/{docId}/links}, but resolving those
costs an extra HTTP call per document. The current handler is
\strong{scan + classify only}: it returns \code{attachment_urls = character(0)}
and an empty \code{download_status} for every record. A future download
phase will fetch the per-document links and populate the per-section
columns. Reflected as \code{"supported (metadata-only)"} in
\code{get_assessments_coverage()}.
}

